  <h3 id="download_database-h3"><a name="download_database" id=
  "download_database">Terminal Database</a></h3>

  <p>The current terminfo/termcap sources are available via http.
  They require tic/infocmp from ncurses 6.2 or later, since they
  use a feature which was broken in previous releases.</p>

  <p>Here are links to a browsable version of the terminfo
  database:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="/ncurses/terminfo.src.html">The terminfo
      database</a>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/ncurses/terminfo.src-sections.html">Sections
        of the database</a></li>

        <li><a href="/ncurses/terminfo.src-history.html">An index
        of the history-section</a></li>
      </ul>
    </li>

    <li>
      <a href="/ncurses/terminfo.ti.html">The terminfo database</a>
      (colored/large)
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/ncurses/terminfo.ti-sections.html">Sections
        of the database</a></li>

        <li><a href="/ncurses/terminfo.ti-history.html">An index of
        the history-section</a></li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>and here are the database files (see <a href=
  "/ncurses/ncurses.faq.html#compatible_tic"><em>Is ncurses
  terminfo compatible with my system?</em></a> in the FAQ):</p>

  <ul>
    <li><a href="/datafiles/current/terminfo.src.gz">Development
    terminfo source (gzip'd text via http)</a></li>

    <li><a href="/datafiles/current/termcap.src.gz">Development
    termcap source (gzip'd text via http)</a></li>
  </ul>

  <p>You may also find the discussion of <a href=
  "tctest.html">tctest</a> useful.</p>

  <p><a href="/xterm/xterm.html">XTerm</a> has its own <a href=
  "/xterm/terminfo.html">terminfo file</a> and <a href=
  "/xterm/termcap.html">termcap</a> files, which are not part of
  ncurses (see <a href=
  "/xterm/xterm.faq.html#xterm_terminfo"><em>What
  <code>$TERM</code> should I use?</em></a>). I adapt parts of
  xterm's terminfo file for ncurses, and use <a href=
  "man/infocmp.1m.html"><code>infocmp</code></a> (in a script) to
  check for mismatches. Some packagers simply append xterm's file
  to the ncurses terminal database, which creates more problems
  than it solves.</p>

